{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540028"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.01,0.61,0.15,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74068"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1692"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3312"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"8936"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining a laceration to his left hand during a low-speed motor vehicle accident. While reversing his delivery truck on a public road, he collided with a parked car and injured his hand on broken glass. The incident occurred 30 minutes ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears jovial and talkative. His speech is slightly slurred, and he seems mildly unsteady when walking to the examination bed. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, GCS 15 and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals normal power, sensation and reflexes in all limbs. Cranial nerve examination is normal. Secondary survey reveals no evidence of head injury or other trauma. He has a 5 cm laceration across his left palm requiring sutures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent CT brain","Administration of naloxone","Blood alcohol level measurement","Tetanus booster","Immediate wound closure"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a motor vehicle accident where the driver shows signs of impairment that require investigation before proceeding with treatment. The clinical signs including slurred speech and unsteady gait suggest potential intoxication, which must be documented objectively in the context of a road traffic accident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood alcohol level measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it provides objective evidence that may explain the patient\u0027s presentation. This is important for both immediate medical management and potential legal proceedings. Collection of blood for a blood alcohol level is required in Australia for all accidents that occur on a public road. The results may have implications for insurance claims, criminal charges, and transport safety regulations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent CT brain\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at present given the reassuring neurological examination, absence of head trauma, and normal GCS. The patient\u0027s symptoms are more consistent with intoxication than an acute intracranial event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the patient does not show signs of opioid toxicity such as respiratory depression, pinpoint pupils, or decreased consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetanus booster\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially necessary for the laceration, is not the immediate priority. The cause of the patient\u0027s impaired state needs to be established first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate wound closure\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without first documenting and investigating the patient\u0027s impaired state. While the laceration needs attention, establishing the cause of the patient\u0027s altered behaviour takes priority in this road traffic incident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining blood alcohol levels, management would include appropriate documentation, treatment of the hand injury, and consideration of safe discharge planning. The incident should be documented thoroughly as it may have implications for legal proceedings, insurance claims, and transport safety regulations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood alcohol levels should be measured in motor vehicle accidents when impairment is suspected.","Documentation of neurological signs and behaviour is crucial in road traffic incidents.","Objective evidence of intoxication is important for both medical and legal purposes in road accidents."],"references":["Charlton A, Keeble R. Assessing a patient with alcohol intoxication. BMJ [Internet]. 2017 Oct 23;j3227. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/359/sbmj.j3227","\u200cGrenga P. ED Management of the MVC Patient: Pearls and Pitfalls [Internet]. emDOCs.net - Emergency Medicine Education. 2017. Available at: https://www.emdocs.net/ed-management-of-the-mva-patient-pearls-and-pitfalls/\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T13:51:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T13:51:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9421"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":nu